-rw-r--r-- 1 svadlamuri svadlamuri 0 Oct 23 15:47 abc4.xml
-rw-r--r-- 1 svadlamuri svadlamuri 0 Oct 23 15:47 abc5.xml

4) Nano: 

svadlamuri@Varma:~/desktop$ nano file1.txt
svadlamuri@Varma:~/desktop$ cat file1.txt
abc
bcd
efg


                        [ Wrote 4 lines ]
^G Help      ^O Write Out ^W Where Is  ^K Cut       ^T Execute
^X Exit      ^R Read File ^\ Replace   ^U Paste     ^J Justify



> svadlamuri@Varma:~/desktop$ nano abc.cpp ( it identified the c++ extension and others ass well)

 GNU nano 6.2                 abc.cpp *              
  #include<iostream>
  
  
^G Help      ^O Write Out ^W Where Is  ^K Cut       ^T Execute
^X Exit      ^R Read File ^\ Replace   ^U Paste     ^J Justify

to save : ctrl+0 to check file name is ok or rename and ctrl+z

5) Sudo:command is used to administation access to another user 

svadlamuri@Varma:~/desktop$ mkdir newdir
svadlamuri@Varma:~/desktop$ ls
abc.cpp  file1.txt  file2.txt  newdir
svadlamuri@Varma:~/desktop$ rmdir newdir
svadlamuri@Varma:~/desktop$
svadlamuri@Varma:~/desktop$ ls
abc.cpp  file1.txt  file2.txt
svadlamuri@Varma:~/desktop$ cd ..
svadlamuri@Varma:~$ rmdir newdir
rmdir: failed to remove 'newdir': No such file or directory
svadlamuri@Varma:~$ mkdir newdir
svadlamuri@Varma:~$ ls
bigfile  desktop  f1  file  file1  file2  images  names  newdir
svadlamuri@Varma:~$ sudo newdir
[sudo] password for svadlamuri:
sudo: newdir: command not found
svadlamuri@Varma:~$ mkdir newdir
mkdir: cannot create directory ‘newdir’: File exists
svadlamuri@Varma:~$ sudo -s
root@Varma:/home/svadlamuri# exit
exit

If we want to download any thing.
root@Varma:/home/svadlamuri# sudo apt-get install <command to download>

6) Top: View active process live with their system usage.

- It will change every 3 sec
- Press S , it will set refresh number.
- Filter idle process press(i).
- Quit press q.


7) ECHO: Print any text follows the command /string that is passed an argument.
svadlamuri@Varma:~$ echo helo world
helo world

svadlamuri@Varma:~$ echo "hello world"
hello world

svadlamuri@Varma:~$ myvar="mark"
svadlamuri@Varma:~$ echo $myvar
mark

svadlamuri@Varma:~$ x=10
svadlamuri@Varma:~$ echo "the value of x is $x"
the value of x is 10

svadlamuri@Varma:~$ echo -e 'some \text'
some    ext

svadlamuri@Varma:~$ echo -e 'some \n text'
some
 text
 
svadlamuri@Varma:~$ echo -e 'some \ntext'
some
text


8) CLEAR : CLEAR ALL THE WHAT WE WROTE UPTO NOW .

9) help commands:
whatis cmd
cmd --help
man cmd

10) i/p and o/p redirects(>,>>,<,stdin,stdout and stderr)

There are 3 redirects in Linux
1. Standard input (stdin) and it has file descriptor number as 0
2. Standard output (stdout) and it has file descriptor number as 1
3. Standard error (stderr) and it has file descriptor number as 2
• Output (stdout) - 1
• By default when running a command its output goes to the terminal
• The output of a command can be routed to a file using > symbol
• E.g.
> STDUOUT:(-1)

svadlamuri@LAPTOP-1BR3SJJG:~/file1$ ls -l
